we need 3 steps:
1.add firstKey.pub to GitHub
2.change repo remote to git@github.com:user/repo.git
3.configure SSH to use firstKey

1.we add the public key to the github as testKey (paste entire file)
  setting + ssh and gpg keys + add ssh key

Note: we can test the connection now!
                                      ssh -i ~/IdeaProjects/firstKey -T git@github.com         //use PRIVATE KEY
                                      Enter passphrase for key '/Users/leila/IdeaProjects/firstKey':    ---> 556072
                                      Hi sinafadaie! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.

Note: so passphrase was not local!
      it he password for using private key on github

Note: -i used for defining the secretKey directory
      This is useful because your key is not in the default name/location
      ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
      (without "i" he will use the key on default directory "~/.ssh/id_ed25519"
       it is for tap-sell!)

Note: -t means it for test!
      so GitHub does not give you a shell!
      so no terminal session is opened!
      Do not request an interactive terminal!
      " Hi sinafadaie! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access."


2.when we want to use ssh
  we should change the remote from "https" to "ssh"

  "git remote set-url origin git@github.com:sinafadaie/Git.git"      //if we have remote already
                                                                     //we should change it!

  "git remote add origin git@github.com:sinafadaie/Git.git"          //we have not any remote for Git yet
                                                                     //we just set it as ssh



3.introduce the private key file address instead of default directory (~/.ssh/id_ed25519)
  if we don't do it, we should introduce him the directory each time by "-i"
  for this we should change the "SSH CONFIG FILE"
                                                  nano ~/.ssh/config    //nano is terminal file editor
                                                  open ~/.ssh/config    //os file editor

Host git.tapsell.ir                         Host github.com
    HostName git.tapsell.ir      ---->      HostName github.com
    User git                                User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519          IdentityFile ~/IdeaProjects/firstKey




ssh -T git@github.com          //tested successfully without -i

git remote                     //we have origin based on ssh now!


Note : because we change ssh config file
       if we use ssh-based remote, it will used our firstKey as private key! (in all repositories!)

Note: the origin (remote) on "design pattern 1" is https yet  (origine https://github.com/sinafadaie/Dedign-Pattern-1.git)
      so we are using token there.
      but the origin on "Git" is ssh                          (origin  git@github.com:sinafadaie/Git.git )
      so we are using ssh on git repository!
